🍽 Recipe Data Collection and API Development
📌 Objective

This project parses recipe data from a JSON file, stores it in a MySQL database, and provides REST APIs to manage and query the data.

It demonstrates:

JSON data handling

Database integration

REST API development

Validation and business logic

Clean layered architecture

🏗 Architecture Overview

The application follows a layered design:

Controller → Service → Repository → Database

Controller → Handles HTTP requests and responses.

Service → Contains business logic.

Repository → Handles database operations.

Database → MySQL database storing recipe data.

📂 Project Structure
recipe-api/
│
├── controller/
│     └── RecipeController.java
│
├── service/
│     └── RecipeService.java
│
├── repository/
│     └── RecipeRepository.java
│
├── model/
│     └── Recipe.java
│
├── util/
│     └── JsonDataLoader.java
│
├── resources/
│     ├── application.properties
│     └── US_recipes_null.json
📦 1. JSON Parsing & Data Loading
🔹 File Used
src/main/resources/US_recipes_null.json
🔹 How It Works

The JSON file is automatically parsed when the application starts using a class that implements CommandLineRunner.

Process:

Read JSON file from resources folder.

Convert JSON into Java objects using ObjectMapper.

Extract recipe objects.

Calculate:

total_time = prep_time + cook_time

Check for duplicate titles before saving.

Insert records into MySQL database.

This ensures:

Automatic data loading at startup

No duplicate records

Clean and validated dataset

🗄 2. Database Design
Database: recipe_db
Table: recipes
CREATE TABLE recipes (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    cuisine VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    rating FLOAT,
    prep_time INT NOT NULL,
    cook_time INT NOT NULL,
    total_time INT,
    description TEXT,
    nutrients JSON,
    serves VARCHAR(100)
);
Key Points

id → Unique identifier (auto-generated)

total_time → Calculated before saving

nutrients → Stored as JSON

title → Used to prevent duplicates

🌐 3. REST API Endpoints

Base URL:

http://localhost:8080/recipes
🟢 POST /recipes
Purpose

Add a new recipe to the database.

Required Fields

title

cuisine

prep_time

cook_time

Business Logic

Automatically calculates total_time

Prevents duplicate titles

Returns proper HTTP status codes

Example Request
POST http://localhost:8080/recipes

Request Body:

{
  "title": "Chocolate Cake",
  "cuisine": "Dessert",
  "prep_time": 20,
  "cook_time": 40,
  "description": "A rich chocolate cake...",
  "serves": "6 servings"
}
Success Response (201 CREATED)
{
  "id": 2,
  "title": "Chocolate Cake",
  "cuisine": "Dessert",
  "prep_time": 20,
  "cook_time": 40,
  "total_time": 60,
  "description": "A rich chocolate cake...",
  "serves": "6 servings"
}
Error Responses
Scenario	Status Code
Missing required fields	400 BAD REQUEST
Duplicate title	409 CONFLICT
🟢 GET /recipes
Purpose

Retrieve all recipes.

GET http://localhost:8080/recipes

Returns all stored recipes.

🟢 GET /recipes/top
Purpose

Retrieve top-rated recipes.

Query Parameter
limit (optional, default = 5)
Example
GET http://localhost:8080/recipes/top?limit=2
Response
{
  "data": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "title": "Sweet Potato Pie",
      "rating": 4.8
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "title": "Chocolate Cake",
      "rating": 4.7
    }
  ]
}
🔄 Application Flow
🔹 On Application Startup

Application starts.

Database connection is established.

JSON file is parsed.

Data is validated and transformed.

Records are inserted into database.

Server is ready on:

http://localhost:8080
🔹 On API Request

Client sends HTTP request to localhost.

Controller receives the request.

JSON request body is converted to Java object.

Service layer applies business logic.

Repository saves or retrieves data.

Response is returned as JSON.

⚙ Technologies Used

Java 17

Spring Boot

Spring Data JPA

MySQL

Jackson (JSON parsing)

Maven

🚀 How to Run Locally
1️⃣ Create Database
CREATE DATABASE recipe_db;
2️⃣ Configure Database Credentials

Update:

src/main/resources/application.properties
3️⃣ Run Application
mvn spring-boot:run

Application will run at:

http://localhost:8080
📌 Testing APIs Locally

Use:

Postman

curl command

Any REST client

All APIs are available at:

http://localhost:8080/recipes
